Friday,January 1, 1932

Spent the entire day and evening working on the paper in the triangular arrangement of numbers as suggested by Prof. Bell. Practically finished it.

Page Edit History:

Saturday January 2, 1932

From noon until evening misc. filing including bringing to date the San Diego County maps for amphibian and lizards.
In the evening checked over the third galley proof of the Snake dance paper.
~~~~~(Jan 3rd Cont.)~~~~~
As of this date things are fairly well up to date. All rattlers are counted (except last Platteville lot)and put away. All reports are practically finished. San Diego County records are up to date; all card files are up to date.
Loaned Cook $20.00 today to be repaid in March. (Repaid OK).
Spent most of the afternoon and evening on the proof of the snake dance paper.
The first draft of the paper on the prime triangle is finished.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 10/12/2011 06:00 PM

Sunday January 3, 1932

This morning I checked over the 5 Banning specimens from the National Museum and other misc. work.
Then went down to National City and saw Mrs. Melling at 220 E. 3rd St. Talked over collecting and preserving. The following are a few items of information mentioned by her. M. piceus is very common at San Jose, much more so than M. lateralis. M.f.frenatus does not seem to occur at San Jose. On San Pedro Marter there is a salamander (E.croceater?). Worm snakes are moderately common at San Jose (may be confused with A. pulchra). Frogs and toads are plenty at both points. There is a water dog at San Antonio creek where there is permanent water (T. toropus?). Boas are moderately common at San Jose. Gopher snakes are common at San Jose; one was found in a hens nest trying to eat the eggs. One killed a little chicken; another was trying to eat goose eggs; the goose was fighting it. Described L.californiae but Mrs. Melling did not recall having seen such a snake.
(Continued Jan 2)

Tuesday January 5, 1932

Working on rate case tonight
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(June 19th Cont.)
1 gopher M DOR Checking Station, Brown spots, Brush-trees.
1 gopher L DOR Lemon Cove. Grass
1 Boyles King L DOR Orange hurst Orange grove and oat field. Light brown, narrow light stripes
1gopher L DOR at Lindsay. Orange groves. Brown spots.
1 Thamnophis sirtalis infernalis L DOR Lindsay Field and irrigated orange grove. Plenty red on this specimen.
1 gopher M DOR at Richgrove. grass. Saved this specimen
Hylas were heard at Famoso
We reached Bakersfield at about 8pm and started around the Maricopa-Taft Loop. The night was perfect but only three snakes were seen all Araizonas recently run over but all fortunately in good condition to preserve.
1 Arizona M DOR Emidio
1 Arizona M DOR 3 mi W of Emidio
(June 19 continued on Jan 6th)

Wednesday January 6, 1932

Working on rate case tonight
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
June 19 continued from Jan. 5th
1 Arizona S DOR North shore Buena Vista Lake. There is plenty water in the lake this year.
Hylas were heard near Greenfield
We reached our auto camp at midnight. Very tired. Miles for the day 277. The car had worked terribly especially at high altitudes. The slightest hill required low gear. Cleaning the the screens at Visalia last night did no good.
Miles for the trip thus far 1373

Thursday January 7, 1932

Working on rate case
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(June 20th Cont.)
1 Gopher L DOR grass and rocks Sunnybrook Retreat
1 Gopher M DOR Tehachapi. Orchards.
On the way up the grad to Tehachapi there are a number of granite outcrops. Some are railry rounding, but no flakes were seen. On the down grade into the Mohave the seems to be no granite. No Yuccas were noted on the upgrade.
1 Gopher M DOR Monolith grass. Brown blotches - rather light. Found this on when going back to hunt glasses when had fallen out.
1 Toad DOR Monolith; B.c. halophilus. Central line quite clear.
the first scattered tree yuccas are seen just west of Cameron. The descent to the Mohave vegetation is rather sudden. The country is hilly - almost mountainous and barren. There are considerable numbers of scattered rocks.
Hunted for a few moments at Cameron. Saw S. magister and C. collaris.
1 Red Racer M DOR Cameron Lt. brush and rocks Hills.
(Cont. on Jan 8th)

Friday, January 8, 1932

Philharmonic
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(June 20th Continued from Jan 7th)
Yuccas are thicker at La Rose. Here we hunted in an extensive yucca forest in a narrow valley. Collected 3 X.vigilis, S. magister and Whips.
Cally noted at Warren
1 Arizona S DOR Denis (LA co) Brush.
1 Red Racer L DOR Vincent Brush.
1 Gopher S DOR 6 mi E of Saugus (Solant?) Brush-fields.
1 Boyles King Caught on the road at Galivan. First thought he had been run over but he was ok next day. This was about 8:30; dark, no moon.
Hylas were heard at Capistrano and Del Mar.
Reached home at 10:10. Miles for the day 304.3; for the trip 1680

Sunday January 10, 1932

Miscellaneous filing and accounts this morning.
Left for San Francisco this afternoon.

Cook working on the rattlers lately received in exchange from Field museum and Harvard.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(June 12 Continued)
1 C. silus DOR 4 mi. W. of Maricopa Juct = Emidio Sta. grass - light sage
1 C. silus DOR 12 mi. W of Maricopa Juct. grass - light brush.
Hunted here in the brush fora short time but saw not lizards.
1 A.e. occidentalis M DOR 3 mi. E. of Maricopa (=Pentland) Grass - oil fields. Saved head.
This road across the southern tip of the San Joaquin ought to be good for night snakes. The county looks too flat and bare for lizards but C. silus evidently occurs there. We saw none alive.
From Maricopa to McKittrick there is too much oil development to expect
(June 12 continued on Jan 11)

Monday January 11, 1932

In San Francisco
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(June 12 continued from Jan 10)
reptiles. One whiptail was seen in Santa Maria Valley west of McKittrick.
Climbing over the Temblar Range west of McKittrick the country is rather bare, although at the highest there are some rock outcrops and a few trees. Might be called upper Sonoran. Hunted for short periods at several points but nothing was seen - not a single lizard. It was warm but not uncomfortable.
In the Carizo Plain we went southward around Soda Lake. Hunted at several points in grass and light bush but did not see a single lizard. There are a few scattered rocks. This was about noon. Close to the lake the brush is about knee high; eastward it was mostly grass, Westward around Summler there are wheat fields.
We now crossed the Calienteand Pozo range and hunted at a few points. There are several long grades. The country is upper Sonoran almost Transition at the tops. Two deer were seen a doe and fawn. There are several rock
(Continued Jan 12)

Tuesday January 12, 1932

In San Francisco
Saw Slevin for an hour this afternoon.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(June 12 continued from Jan 11)
outcrops. On the west slope of the Pozo mts the brush is very thick and there is some granite but it is hard and without flakes. Along the Salina's River it looks good for amphibians.
We reached Santa Margarita at 3:30 and decided to go on to S.F. Ther eis almsot no chance for collecting in the Salena's Valley as the low DOR list shows.
1 Gopher M DOR King City Fields.
What was probably a small Boyles King was seen on the San Juan grade but couldn't stop.
Reached Palo Alto at 8:30; waited for Alice until 9:30. Reached San Francisco at 10:30. Miles for the day 377; for this trip 579. The car was working badly; 7.4 miles/gal today.
Was much disappointed in the Carrizo Plain country and likewise the Pozo range. Expected to see a lot of material here but as the list shows it was very scant. With heavy traffic from Santa Margarita north the lack

Thursday January 14, 1932

Tired out with rate case.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(June 13th Continued)
Caliente. Both are dark chocolate brown with very faint markings. Either has a well defined dorsal stripe; rather they are like San Diego Co. mixed Kings - that is the markings are variable, but with no even dorsal stripe anywhere. In other words the markings are nearer boylii than californiae but are very faint. There is a jagged dorsal line connecting the rings but no rings cross the ventral surface which is uniformly dark. This is probably the most important characteristic.

Sonora episcopa
4 Specimens (13770-3) from C?? are unicolor like Oklahoma specimens; there is no indication of a dorsal stripe. They are of course formalin preserved. They are quite large; considerably larger than any Imperial Co. specimen I have seen.
12601-2 (Oklahoma?) and 12709 (3 mi No of Goldthwaite Mills Co. Tex are also unicolor - 5549 (4 mi. N of Blythe Juct., San BernardinoCo.) and 5610 (Herber) have distinct dorsal stripes, now white, probably originally pink.
Uta mearnsi Cabezon, Banning, Snow Creek
(Continued on Jan 15th)

Notes:

lwilliams

2nd paragraph: 4 specimens from C??

Monday January 18, 1932

Record from L-T Murray.
Unmistakable photo.
C. lepidus Brewster Co. Tex.
4 mi W. of Alpine Aug 1928

Hylas heard tonight
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(June 17 continued)
at 3:15 and arrived at 7. Stopped along the road at several points and overturned many logs and stones but found nothing. A good many Skellies were seen along here on the rocks; noted at Inspiration Point.
Hunted along the creek in Peregoy Meadows for a short time and got 2 small Rana boylii sierrae. This was in water running out of snow drifts. Large egg masses were also collected; Probably Hyla regilla. As usual the frogs were on the bank and took refuge in the grass on the bottom where the stream was moving rather swiftly. Two or three larger frogs were seen and lost. The eggs were attached to twigs in more quite waters.
After putting up at the hotel we returned to Pothole meadows and hunted
(Continued on Jan 19)

Wednesday Janurary 20, 1932

(June 18th Continued)
It was found in the ditch under a bank not far from where the track crossed the road.
Hunted in the granite near Oakhurst. Got a Whiptail and saw several Skellies. There is much granite along the road hereabouts but it is all hard and moss covered - no flakes. A Skelly was seen near Coarse Gold.
1 Gopher L DOR Oakhurst grass
1 Gopher L DOR Coarse Gold grass
1 Racer (M. lateralis) or garter, probably the former, lost crossing the road at Willow Glen. Grass-brush.
1 Gopher L caught crossing the road at Bellview grass. This was at 6:30 PM
Hylas were heard in irrigation ditches at Sanger, Parlier, Reedly, and Dinulra.
Although much driving was done in the San Joaquin Valley after dark, no snakes were seen - they cannot be common.
This was a rather tiring day. The road from Wawona including the side trip to the Mariposa grove and particularly the section from Sugar
(Continued on Jan 21)

Thursday January 21, 1932

(June 18th continued from Jan 20)
Pine to near Friant is hard slow driving. Evidently we took the wrong road here, we should have gone via Bass Lake and Northfork instead of Coarse Gold, for a new oiled road seems to have been almost completed over the former route, but my map did not show it.
In addition the care was working terribly - had to go into low on the slightest hill; had to back up hill once.
Reached Visalia at 10:00. Miles for the day 164.5; for the trip 1097. As hard work as 350 miles of ordinary travel.

Tuesday February 2, 1932

Wend to El Cajon Rotary today. Broadway ext. 30 miles. A cold wet day, nothing seen
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(May 29th Continued from Feb 3rd)
Wickenburg more arid and rolling; tree cactus and yuccas.
1Patch-nose DOR Wickenburg Creek-mesquite hills.
1 Sonoran Racer DOR 6 mi N.W. of Morristown (Hot Springs Jnct) contained a Holbrookia texana and a Whiptail. Brush and river.
Also one S. magister observed at the same point. Morristown is a cactus-mesquite plain. Vegetation is thin; it is arid.
There were 2 Gophers DOR at the New River Bridge 1/2 way bet Marinette and Peoria. Cultivated fields. One was saved.
Stopped at Glendale to pickle specimens
Reached Phoenix at 810 (P.T.) and ate supper.
1 long nose L DOR 20 mi W. of Phoenix. This is between Perry Ville and Coldwater probably nearer the latter.
1 Marcy's Garter DOR L at Hassa Yampa. Gila Bend at 1030. Miles for the day 235.5; for the trip 579.0

Wednesday, February 3, 1932

(May 29th Continued from Feb 4th)
cactus and lava. Inquired for T.C. Biggs but he was out.
Date Creek (and the country to the north) is a large grassy plain with some rock outcrops. Also cactus.
1 Patchnose M caught crossing the road just south of Date; Creek-brush.
At the south end of Date Valley there is much mesquite; then bare tumbled rocks, much like those about Mt. Springs.
It is noticeable that the country became more arid as we go south and downward.
Piedmont is a rocky rolling plain with cactus, small brush and much rock. It is considerably more arid then Date.
Uta ornata was noted 3 mi. N of Congress Juct; and S. magister 2 mi N.
1 Large gopher DOR Congress Jnct. Light brush and a wash.
At Congress Jnct. there are rolling hills, some rock outcrops, much mesquite.
A large gopher was caught crossing the road 5 mi. S. of Congress Jnct Light brush. 7PM (M.T.)
(Continued Feb. 2nd)

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 06/23/2014 02:18 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:28 PM

Thursday February 4, 1932

(May 29th continued from May 26th)
Krikland is also a large valley but is more arid than Skull Valley. There are some rock outcrops south of Kirkland. On one of these a C. collaris was seen. Can be called Kirkland.
At Kirkland we leave the railroad and follow the highway via Yava.
We stopped at a rocky granite ledge, 2.6 miles north of Hillside. This is in the McCloud mts. Here we found a Gila Monster DOR. Brush (thick) and rocks. Didn't know they occurred in such country.
Here we collected a number of species of lizards including 2 Xantusia arizonae. Whiptails were seen but not collected; also a Coleonyx was found under a rock flake but lost. He was distinctly striped; not mottled.
The patch nose collected here was in a bush about 2 ft above ground. It had eaten a Uta ornata.
Hillside (as seen from the road) is a great, grass-covered plain to the east and rocky rolling hills, to the south. Here there is plenty of
(Continued on Feb 3rd)

Saturday February 6, 1932

(March 245h, continued from Feb. 7th)
Hylas were heard at Fallbrook, Vista, Buena, San Marcos, Escondido, Painted Rocks, Poway, Miramar (Entered on map).
No live snakes were seen today.
Dead snakes were see as follows.
1 Patch nose med DOR County Line. Desert. This was a usual desert light colored specimen.
1 Gopher juvenile DOR Beaumont, grass.
1 Pacific rattler large fields DOR West end of Los Alamos Valley (5 mi NE of Temecula junction)
1 Juvenile Gopher DOR Rainbow. Light brush
The few snakes seen, particularly the single one on the desert indicates that it was too early for snakes to be out. Probably too cold nights on the desert.
Saw no sidewinder tracts.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 10/25/2011 11:10 PM
  • lwilliams 10/25/2011 11:09 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:28 PM

Sunday February 7, 1932

(March 24th, continued from Feb. 8)
Umas were seen but they are very wild (maybe because it was afternoon) When started they took to ground holes at once. Worked very hard for a single specimen. One Cally was collected; also Utas were seen but not collected. Umas evidently followed this line of sand hills and so reach the whitewater dunes. The latter by the way, are very close to the highway and would be much easier to reach than where we did hunt. This afternoon hunt demonstrated once again that lizards should be hunted in the morning; one should travel in the afternoon.
We next hunted in the San Jacinto River north of San Jacinto. Turned over logs looking for Batrachoseps and although we found none we got Scaphiopus, Bufo, Hyla regilla and Utas. Skellies were seen but not collected.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 06/23/2014 04:46 PM
  • lwilliams 10/25/2011 11:21 PM

Monday February 8, 1932

(March 24th Cont)
section of desert. Here we collected Utas and Whips. Callys were seen but not collected. The near road opens up some fine near desert country; there is some sandy country where Umas might be formed but by no means certain.
Cross Carrizo wash at 96.1; U.S. 99 at 106.8; Riverside County line 130.1
Evidently the new highway meets US99, 2 mi. above Kane spr.
We hunted for quite a while 2 mi N. of highway intersection having reached this point at 10:30. We collected a number of species of lizards which will be properly recorded in the collection list. Umas were moderately common but wilder than in the sand hills. At this point there are several sand dunes of considerable size with scattered hummocks between. Weather clear, no wind, moderately warm.
After lunch we stopped at a point about 3 mi W. of Indian Wells on the Palm Springs road, and hunted hard in the sand dunes east of the wash
(Mar 24 continued on Mar 2 Feb 7th)

Thursday February 18, 1932

Talked on Snake Dance at San Diego Museum this afternoon.
Theo Tausch a collector was in today and tried to sell me some snakes. He had many queer yarns to tell. He collects rattlers for a living. Got 1400+ at some point in Napa Co. in one day. Rattlers don't like blue. He picks them all up with his bare hands. Has only been bitten twice. Gets $0.50 a pound for the common ones. Largest rattler he ever caught was 9 1/2 ft. long near Roosevelt Dam in Ariz. Has found dens of 50 or 60 in San Diego; usually all one kind together. He also finds ruber mild tempered. He can track rattlers by sex gland smell in spring. He thinks they travel up to 60 or 70 miles from their winter dens (in Colorado) and has checked this by tying threads to rattlers.

Friday February 19, 1932

Sent out first lot of snake dance papers.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(Continued from April 26th)
cold and windy. Here we collected 1 each of X. vigilis, C. variegatus, and S. magister all under common yuccas.
We hunted for a while 1 mi. W. of Mountain pass. Here it was very cold. There are three kinds of yuccas including tree yuccas. Got 2 X. vigilis under common yuccas; none under tree yuccas.
Hunted at 1 PM at Yucca Grove which is also called Yucca Station. This is 5 miles each of Halloran Spring. Here we collected X. vigilis and S. magister. Utas were seen under yuccas but lost. The X. vigilis are under common yuccas even though the tree yuccas predominant. They prefer thoroughly rotted pieces closely adhering to the ground.
Looked for Umas in a fine sand dune 16 miles west of Baker but had no luck. Too cold and windy. They certainly ought to be found there.
Yerno at 3:45, very cold and windy; decided to go home. Rain off and on all the way to Escondido
(continued Feb 20th)

Monday March 7, 1932

Spent the evening culling separates
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(April 24th continued from March 6th)
Utas and Whips. Phil saw a large Chuck. Miles 437.2, elevation 3555.
Phil hunted for a few moments at the north end of Mesquite Dry Lake and got 1Uta, also hunted in the sand dunes just east of Las Vegas and got 1 Uta Wind now too strong to expect anything.

This part of the trip was disappointing; the country between Arrowhead Junction and Las Vegas does not look very good; miles and miles of alluvial fans. Probably plenty of Whips and Callys in the morning. There is a fairly good tree yucca forest north of Searchlight but few fallen trunks are seen. Saw not sand hill which might be suspected of harboring Umas.
In the evening ran down the road past Sloan. It was quite cool although without much breeze. Caught a Rhinocheilus, L, crossing the road 15 mi S. of Las Vegas(=Sloan). This was at 8:30. It was quite cold and the snake was noticeably so. He may be been after a mouse which was playing in the road.

Saturday March 12, 1932

Splitting separates this afternoon
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(April 23rd Continued)
in a greenwood bush when first seen; ran into a large crack and was excavated with difficulty. Also got a leopard lizard; he hid under rocks twice and did not go down holes.
Whiptails and Callys crossing the road at Lavic. Callys at Argos.
We stopped at noon 1/2 mil W. of Ludlow and hunted for nearly an hour. Here there was a sand dune or sand slide on the lee or east side of a rocky hill. The sand was free and loose. Stopping primarily to see if Umas might be found here and they were in evidence at once. They were moderately common but we only got three for they were wild. They used their usual tactics; i.e. run around a bush and swing into the sand. Sometimes they fail to bury their tails.
Callys were common. The large males bench on the rocks and bob up and down. They often run a long distance before stopping; at other times they turn suddenly and hide behind a bush. They run
(Continued on March 13)

Sunday March 13, 1932

Worked on prime paper this morning.
Left for San Francisco at 2:15
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(April 23rd continued from March 12)
with their tails curled over their backs and are rather easy to distinguish. But leopards, Dips and Whips run much the same and are not easy to distinguish (no leopards seen at this point)
Whips usually stop before entering the bush they intend to take refuge in and then go in by the usual jerky motion. Dips stop inside the bush, but go into ground holes if closely perused. Dips are very easy to shoot as they are seen to feel safe if in a bush; they often stop in the first bush they come to unless badly scared.
No Utas were noted here at Ludlow. Philip found a complete 1/3 grown tortoise shell. Evidently these tortoises have some enemy which is able to get out the meat.
By this time at Ludlow the wind had died down and it was moderately warm.
We ate lunch at Ludlow; also changed a tire which had started to leak. This was later repaired at Needles.
Started east from Ludlow at 2:10
(Continued on March 14)

Wednesday March 16, 1932

(March 19th, continued from Mar. 17)
Few made any attempt to escape and fewer still were lost. We got all sizes from very large females to young. 2 pairs were mating, one on land and one in the water. In both cases the female was larger. We caught only 2 more toads.
Miles for the evening trip 6.8.
Returned to hotel at 8:40.
This was certainly the best Rana hunting I ever had. The evening was cool and comfortable - not cold, but still no chance for snakes.
No snakes seen today alive or dead.
Total miles for the day (uncorrected) 292.6 (will make corrections when speedometer has been checked).
The termites were Reticulitermes tibialis (identification by Paul Harvey)

Thursday March 17, 1932

are quite scattered. Also found under a branch a half grown S. magister quite dormant with cold. This is a rolling mesa with greasewood and a few yuccas; it ought to be fine lizard country in hot weather.
We reached Victorvilled at 6:10. Miles uncorrected 285.8
In the evening at about 8 o'clock we went up the road to the highway bridge over the Mohave river. Hylas could be heard everywhere, in the marshes and along the river as well. We stopped at the bridge and listened for quite a while before the first B. californicus could be heard, but this was probably due to the noise the Hylas were making.
We decided to look for Bufos and almost immediately Phil got one at the top of the bluff. So we went down along the river. We found Rana aurora draytonii very plentiful and easy to catch and all together we got 40. It was only necessary to shine the flashlight on them, whether in the water or on the sand and they could be picked up.
(Continued on March 16)

Friday March 18, 1932

(March 19th continued)
We traveled by way of Neenach, Fairmont, Lancaster, Palmdale, Little Rock, Leano.
We first stopped at the yucca forest 4 1/2 miles west of Fairmont; this was about 1:30 in the afternoon. It was still cool and cloudy. Here we found Xantusia vigilis hunting good and we caught 25 all together. Mostly they were underneath dead yucca limbs, particularly those still retaining leaves; less often in the limbs or under bark. When discovered they try to escape in the debris. It was quite moist where they are found. They are nearly black when uncovered, but soon get lighter. They probably live on termites which are very plentiful in the dead stems. We saw 2 other lizards, probably utas.
Lancaster at 227.0 is quite sage brushy.
At 5:30 we stopped 10.2 mi S.W. of Victorville and got 16 more Xantusias mostly under dead yucca branches. Here they seemed to be lighter in color (maybe because it was dryer here). They were mostly under smooth branches without leaves here. The branches here
(Continued on March 17)

Saturday March 19, 1932

This morning at 6:21 started for Los Angeles with GG and Phil. A cool overcast day. County line at 54.1. Was overhauled by a cop north of San Clemente. Said I was going 55 when the speedometer registered 42. Tested the car against RR mile posts and found 40 miles on the speedometer equals about 47 1/2 miles. Distance will have to be corrected in the same ratio.
Reached Southern Pacific Station at 9:21 and picked up Shorty. Nothing seen enroute.
After some shopping we started from Los Angeles for the Antelope Valley via the Ridge Route. The weather continued cool and cloudy. There is no granite on the Ridge Route. Turns into the Antelope Valley at 190.8.
The upper or west end of the Antelope Valley is moderately level and mostly cultivated. There are many abandoned orchards. It probably was once a thinly covered sagebrush plain, looking more like a scutulatus country than it does now. East of Del Sur it becomes more dry and sagebrushy than and then melts into the Mohave desert x
(Continued March 18)

Sunday March 20, 1932

Today we returned to San Diego from Victorville via San Bernardino, Claremont, Chino, Corona, Temescal Canyon and the inland road from Elsinore.
Last night it blew hard and this morning at Victorville a cold hard wind was blowing off the snow clad mountains. It was much too cold for collecting and very disagreeable. At about 9:20 we wend to Dead Man's Point about 11 mi E. of Victorville. We first stopped in the yuccas about 3 mi E of Victorville and got 2 Xantusia vigilis.
At Dead Man's point got one Uta stans and a Xantusia vigilis, both under rock flakes. Also saw a Skelly but lost him. This looks like fine country; the granite is about the same quality as at Mountain Springs. There are some fairly good flakes. The Xantusia was under a very large cap rock, at least 3 ft. above ground. So they do run on rocks.
We now returned to Victorville; then stopped 13 mi S.W. of Victorville near south end of Yucca belt. Much too cold for Xantusias Found 1 Skelly under a branch. He was quite dormant with cold.
(Continued to March 11)

Thursday March 24, 1932

This morning at 6:08 we started for the desert; entire family plus Alice. A fine clear quiet day; a little fog in the low places in the early morning hours. Warm on the desert but not hot, just a little to warm for comfort in walking.
Route: El Cajon Ave, El Cajon, Lakeside, Ramona, Julian, Banner, Sentenac, Narrows, New highway to a point near Kane Springs, north through Indio, Palm Springs, Banning, Moreno Grade, San Jacinto, Hemet, Winchester, Temecula, Rainbow, Fallbrook, Escondido. Reached home at 7:50. Total miles 322. (Note: The speedometer seems to be ok on distance but no speeds.) Miles in SD county morning 92; afternoon count to Fallbrook only a/c darkness making it 9 mi.
Between the foot of Sentenac Canyon and The Narrows the Utas were plentiful on the rocks and quite continuously. Other lizards were not seen except possibly a S. magister seen by Philip.
The first stop was made 4 mi inside the San Diego County line in a rather rocky
(Continued on Feb 8th)

Friday March 25 1932

(April 3rd Continued)
Turned over a few logs but saw nothing. There are granite boulders at several points on the grade but none appear of good quality. Skellies were seen at several points. The creeks and river are poor; too many boulder; no soil.
Heard Hyla arenicolor at Strawberry Creek and noted Skellies here; also Skellies at North fork crossing.
Hunted at the San Jacinto Bridge north of San Jacinto. skellies and Utas were thick. Got only 1 Toad; also many little toads one of which is a Spade foot. Many polywogs in sight.
On snake DOR at Rainbow; couldn't stop as was passing another care at the time.

Wednesday March 30, 1932

(April 2nd continued)
In these damp canyons we found 2 small Triturus crawling loose; also a large one in a hole under a stone where it was quite dry. Then we found many in the water in the creek. Many pairs in coitu. Also eggs.
Batrachoseps were found at several points from 3 mi E. of Hot Springs to 2 mi W. They were found under both stones and logs; but were more plentiful under the latter.
One Toad DOR 1 mi E of Capistrano B.c.h.
took both regilla and arenicolor near Hot Springs.
There is some granite on mt. tops and some boulder in creek but we saw none suitable for Xantusia close to road.
Stopped at San Mateo Creek bridge at about 7:30 and collected R.a. draytonii, H. regilla and 4 B. californicus. For the first time found the latter int he water and probably calling as trills were heard all around. Did not actually see one trill. Also stopped an heard the trill at Oceanside.

Saturday April 2, 1932

This afternoon went to San Juan Hot Springs with Kranzthor.
Started at 1:10; returned at 9:30. A clear cool day; quite cold along the ocean.
Total miles 162.0. Miles in San Diego County in daylight 56.
Little was seen on the road; in fact nothing along the coast except a large boyles king at Morena which had been checked in before.
The road up Hot Spring's canyon looks good, ought to be a fine trip when completed through to Elsinore.
2 mi. W. of Hot Spring's there was a large M. lateralis in the road. Stopped and looked for him in the brush. Must have stepped on him without seeing him as we found the loose end of his tail still squirming.
Got a medium garter at 3 mi beyond Hot Spring which was .3 mi W. of where we turned around.
At this point and westward we hunted at several small damp canyons' also along the river. Got Skellies and and alligator; saw no utas

Sunday April 3, 1932

Today went to Tahquitz Lodge and also San Jacinto with Philip. A clear warm day. Total miles 240. Miles in San Diego County in daylight 119. Started at 8:15; returned at 6:50. Few snakes were seen, none alive.
1 P.c. annectens L DOR Miramar grass-brush
1 do S DOR Poway grass
1 G.s. webbii DOR Red mt. Brush.
Hunted for a while in the large granite boulders 1.4 mi N. or Riv-S.D. Co. Line. Orcuttis and Skellies are here in abundance, but the rocks are n.g. Too hard; rounded edges but without flakes.
Found the same true of the rocks in and between the several valleys between Temecula and Winchester. The rocks are all too hard to flake although there were plenty of oructtis, skellies and utas. Also an occasional whiptail. Looks like good snake country, but we saw none.
We hunted especially 11 mi. S. of Winchester (call it Auld) and 1 mi S. of Winchester. Dead horned toads at Auld; also at Hemet.
At Tahquitz Lodge the country doesn't look particularly inviting; too dry.
(Continued to March 25)

Friday April 22, 1932

Today at 2:10 PM started for Hoover Dam with Philip. A cool, breezy day after a windstorm lasting several days. Increasingly cold as we progressed. At San Bernardino said to have been 34 the night before. Very cold and windy when we reached the desert. Could not expect any reptiles to be out, or any to have been out in the daytime. Two mice were seen on the road; evidently they stand cold better than reptiles. Altogether an exceedingly unfortunate time to have to start on the trip.
Reached Barstow at 8:30; miles to county line 65.1; total miles for the day 201.9.
1 Horn Toad DOR Poway grass
1 B.c. halophilus DOR Escondido City. A good many toads were seen altogether as it had rained the day before.
Skellies were seen on a rock near a pool at Escondido.
1 Oreganus juv. DOR Fallbrook; grass-brush
1 Patchnose med DOR Red Mt. grade; brush. (usual dark coastal phase)
1 B.c. halophilus DOR Rainbow (grass)
1 Horn Toad || || ||

Sunday April 23, 1932

This morning at Barstow we wake up at 7:45. It was cold with a strong wind blowing. Started for Needles at 9 AM
1 Patchnose M DOR 5 mi. E. of Barstow (=Nebo) Thin brush; rocky ground. Usual desert light colored specimen.
We stopped for 1/2 hour (9:30-10) at the Daggett bridge over the Mohave River. Although the stream was a considerable river at Barstow at Daggett it has dwindled to a trickle that can be stepped across. There were no polywogs in the pool and little plant life - probably Alkali. Dips and Whips were seen here, but were not collected; collected Callys and a P. playrhinos, the latter in sand. Here it was still cool and breezy.
Stopped for quite a while at Hector (240.5). It had now become somewhat warmer and less breezy; about 70 to 75 at a guess. There is a large outcrop of black lava partly smothered in sand. Found a small tortoise shell nearly whole. Callies were seen but no collected. Utas are on the rocks; Whips usually on the level spots where there are bushes and small broken rocks scattered on the sand. Got a chuck (as did Philip likewise); he was
(Continued on March 12)

April 24, 1932

Started from Needles at 9:30 after getting gas, oil, and supplies. Got some formalin to play safe. This took over 1/2 hr. It was a clear warm day with a mild breeze.
Had expected some DOR snakes on the highway but had no luck.
Cally crossing the road at Ibis. Searchlight road branches north from highway at 400.0.
Cally 1.6 mi. N. of this point; call it Aarowhead Junction. (between Ibis and Bannock)
One very large tortoise at the roadside 2.6 miles north of the junction. Sandy rocky soil; scattered brush. Same locality as above.
Cross the Nevada state line at 413.5.
We stopped and hunted for a while 1 mi. N. of the state line. This is an alluvial fan with brush, yucca, and cactus (Common yucca, not tree yucca). All kinds of lizards seen were collected. Warm but cooling breeze.
Xantusia vigilis and Skellies are under dead yucca bark and are very hard to get.
whips and Utas 3 mi. N. of State line;

Monday April 25, 1932

This morning was cool, windy and partly overcast. Our party started for the dam at 7:20. Northmore wen in our car.
1 Rhinocheilus L, DOR entrance to Boulder City. Rocky brush. This snake had wide black bands 4 times as wide as the narrow white or cream bands. The latter were slightly suffused with orange. The black was solid on top but on the sides there was a triangle of light centered scales, the base of the triangle being below. This was 1.2 mi. W. of the center of Boulder City.
As the other machine was not yet arrived we drove down the Vegas Wash to the river on the new paved road. Was now cold, windy and overcast. Saw 1 Cally DOR halfway down and 1 leopard DOR near Boulder City.
Back at Boulder City at 8:45; met the party at the home of H.O. Walts of the SS.P.Co.

Tuesday April 26, 1932

Day opened cold, cloudy and windy. Let Philip sleep as there would evidently be no hunting today. Such rotten luck to be over in this country, so rarely reached and then to have no hunting. Today starts even worse than yesterday.
P. platyrhinos DOR at 3.7 mi. out of Las Vegas.
First stop 5.4 miles north of Jean. Here are common yuccas and a few tree yuccas. Got 12 Xantusia vigilis, 1 S. magister and saw but did not catch utas. It was very cold and windy. The lizards were more or less dormant. Some of the rotting yuccas seemed to create warmth. Found the Xantusias mostly under yuccas branches without leaves and near live yuccas, but not always. All of these were under common yuccas. This point is 1.9 mi. N. of the railway crossing.
Raining hard at Jean
Medium gopherDOR at State Line Wells. Rocky desert, light brush. State Line Wells is .6 mi E. of the actual state line.
Hunted again in the yuccas 1.2 mi NE of Lakeview Junction Still very
(Continued Feb. 19th)

Sunday May 1, 1932

Started for the desert from Cuyamaca this morning at 9:30 with Fowler, Phythian and Sjoblom. Went via Julian and the Narrows. Weiss and De Waard in their own car. Cold in the mountains; warm (almost hot) on the desert. Returned by El Centro and the highway. Windy in the afternoon.
Very few lizards were seen in the Sentenac Canyon or San Felipe Wash. However we did not stop to hunt here.
The first stop was at a sand dune 17 mi. W. of the highway intersection. This dune is on the east slope of a mountain and is large with good sand. Looks ideal for Uma. We hunted hard for them but got none. I saw one lizard that might have been a Uma - can't be sure. Will have to try this early in the morning some time. It was warm with some breeze and the time about 12:30. Saw many snake tracks by the borders. Got Callys, Whips and Dips.
One red racer medium 14 mi W of the intersection. Light brush; desert
(Continued to April 29th)

Sunday May 8, 1932

This morning we started from Indio at 8:35; a clear and moderately warm day.
1 Sonora L DOR at 4.8 Sandy desert. no red. Call this Indian Wells.
We hunted in the sand hills at 6.7 until 9:50. Got a Cally and a whip.
Saw magister and uta, and maybe Uma but couldn't be sure of the latter. Call this Indian Wells.
1 Leopard lizard DOR at 12.2 Call this Indian Wells. Saved Specimen.
1 Red racer L DOR at 12.6. Sandy desert. Call this Indian Wells. Saved head only.
We next hunted at Whitewater, that is the sand slide near Palm Springs Railroad Station. We first hunted at the smaller dunes S.E. of the cliff; then in the mesquite hummocks opposite the large dune. Stayed here quite a long time. Got Umas, Callies, whips and a Uta graciosa. It was hard work. The Umas are very wild; hard to shoot. Other lizards seemed scarce. Met the Pembertons here; they hunted with us for a short time.
We then wen on through the pass
(Continued May 3rd)

Saturday May 14, 1932

This afternoon at 5:15 started for the desert with Phil & Jack Ward. It was clear and cool. A slight breeze, freshening to the desert where in the early evening, especially on the Mt. Springs grade, it blew quite strongly.
We did not hunting, only traveling, today.
1 Rhinocheilus L Bostonia grass.
Had evidently been run over by next preceding car. Seemed not seriously hurt, so was saved and two days later was still ok. Picked up at 5:45.

Sunday May 15, 1932

This morning we started eastward from Yuma at 7.
1 C.c. mitchellii DOR M Gila mts. Bare Rocks. A gray specimen, badly smashed.
We hunted until 9 25 mi E. of Yuma at the RR overunderpass. Call this ???. This is a sandy, rocky flat. Callys, dips, and Whips were very common.
Whiptails, dips and Callys were noted continuously on the road, both east and west bound. Dips especially were observed at intervals of 2 or three miles. Welton, Tacna, Colfred and Pembroke.
1 Red Racer DOR M Colfred. Desert; light brush.
At the Reptile Inn west of Mohawk. I talked with Rudolph Hale the proprietor. Herron is now in Long Beach.
He had a Boyles King taken on the Gila River nearby. It seemed a typical Boyles. The white bands were narrow but clear. There was an oreganus said to have been taken in the Mohawk mts. but this would require conformation. Hale says coral snakes are found in this vicinity and promised to send me one.
Amongst the species seen in his
(Continued on May 12)

Tuesday May 17, 1932

Milked 50 juvenile Confluentus from Perkins this noon. There may have been 51; the box was partly open and at least 2 got out.
The statistical data were as follows:
10 rattlers with 2 rattles 14.15 gr. each (average)
40 rattlers with 1 rattle 9.97 gr. each.

Total venom 0.1 c.c.
Very difficult to get venom because of the small size. Used lace over the tube.
Later this evening the odd lost specimen turned up on the work bench.

Spent the evening on the first revision of the combined (2 trips) Hoover Dam paper.

Friday May 20, 1932

Recd today from Le Roy a large ringneck. from San Diego
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(May 22nd Continued)
Next hunted in large and thick tree yuccas in Yucca Valley = Warren's Well 1/2 mi E of where road branches to Victorville. Got 5 X. vigilis, they were mostly under stems, sheathed with leaves. Also saw but did not collect Utas, Whips, and magister. This was at 1:40; cool and plesant.
Hunted next at east end of Morongo Valley. Here X. vigilis were taken under regular yuccas.
At 3 P.M. we stopped at the south end of Morongo Valley where there were many scattered boulders. Utas were very common and a number were collected. Whips and Leopards were seen. It was now cool and windy. A little further 2 magisters were seen on rocks.
1 Patchnose M DOR 0 mi N of Whitewater Jnct. This is called Devil's Playground. Creek and rocky hill.
Callys were collected 7 mi N of the Junction and a large magister 6 mi. N of the Junction. Utas were also seen here.

Saturday May 21, 1932

Today at 2 PM started for Twenty-nine Palms with Philip. a Clear warm day.
1 Horned Toad DOR Escondido
1 Boyles King L DOR Vista grass-fields

(Saved specimen)

Arrived at 29 Palms at 7:15. Cool and Windy. 180 miles.
Went up the ??Amboy?? road from 8 to 9:30 Cool and windy. Nothing Seen. It was not too cold for sidewinders. The road is badly corduroyed; it would be difficult to see anything on a road like this; little snakes if present would quite likely have been missed.
At about 4 AM heard toads trilling in the marsh. Think they were B. californicus but can't be sure. Didn't know there was a marsh or we would have hunted toads the night before.
Miles to 29palms 182; inside SD county 65. Total miles for the day 202.

Sunday May 22, 1932

Sunday morning at 29 palms. Cool and windy.
First looked around the marsh but found nothing. There was a large bolt in the rear tire. Changed tires.
Left the hotel at 8:50 and looked for Robt Hunters place. Finally located him. He had in his collection mitches, sidewinders, Red Racers, Phyllorhynchus, Sonora occipitalis, arizona, Chucks, gophers, tortoises, Salvadora. All these caught in the vicinity of 29 palms. Bot from him 2 mitches, 1 Salvadora, 1 Phyllor, 1 Sonora for $5.00, later on the road he gave me a platyrhinos from the same locality. Talked collecting with Hunter for awhile; then hunted in a sand dune between his place and the post office. Collected all kinds of lizards that were except Umas of which at least 3 were seen but none secured. They were exceedingly wary. Then started back.
1 Leopard lizard DOR 29 palms
1 do DOR Warren's Well.
Hunted a short time in regular yuccas at west end of 29 palms valley and got a X. vigilis
(Continued on May 20th)

Thursday May 26, 1932

(May 29th Continued)
They don't seem to be any more common than last summer. Holbrookia is not nearly so plentiful as them. Only 1 X.a. was attached to the rock which fell and this was an underslung flake. of the X.a. LMK 8, Cook 6, PMK 1, Gartz1.
1 gopher S DOR Yarnell Brush-fields. We also caught 2 live C. collaris here.
At Kirkland Jnct. we left the highway and turned west to Kirkland in order to see the character of the Santa Fe country. We went north to Skull Valley, then returned along the road which approximately follows the railroad to the junction with the main highway at Congress.
Skull Valley is a large irrigated Valley. The railroad runs along one side where there is mesquite and other brush. There are some rock outcrops, but not many. Doesn't look like particularly good snake country. The brush is light.
Between Skull Valley and Kirkland the country is rather rough and rolling with some rock.
(Continued on Feb. 4th)

Friday May 27, 1932

Today received from Bill Fay a medium gopher snake from Pacific Beach. This snake squeezed wrist hard enough to hurt and shut off blood. Pulsating use of muscle with deliberate intention to squeeze.

Sunday May 20, 1932

This morning we started north from Wickenburg at 7:55 (P.T.)
Between 8:30 and 9 we hunted at a point 6 mi. N. of Wickenburg. Here we got a number of lizards in brush, mesquite, yuccas and some tree cactus. But on the whole hunting was not good; probably it was too cool. There were many good dead yuccas lying on the ground but they proved barren. S. magister was the only lizard seen and not collected.
1 gopher DOR Congress Juct. Mesquite
1 Hypsiglena L DOR at Desert View Pt. (This is almost at the top of Congress Juct.- Yarnell grade.)
We hunted for Xantusia arizonae just north of the top of the grade (a half mile or so south of the type locality) from 10AM to 1P.M. We worked hard but got only 16 together with some other lizards, a small Hypsiglena and a bat. It was cool and breezy. Flakes (Whether thick or thin) are by no means plentiful. the X.a. are under the thicker flakes, and mostly on the south sides. They are certainly not plentiful. Probably 1/3 of all these seen are lost.
(Continued on May 26)

Monday May 30, 1932

Today we started west from Gila Bend at 7:05.
Whiptails were observed at Aztec and at Stoval; also 1 sidewinder DOR at east base of the Mohawk mts. Rocky desert.
We stopped and hunted for a while in the Mohawk mts. at 9 AM. It was warm but not hot. We got Whiptails which here are plentiful on rocky ground; also observed Uta stans.
Stopped for a few moments at Reptile Inn. Nothing new.
1 P. platyrhinos DOR Pembroke
We hunted for a while in the Gila River bed just north of Ligurta (off the highway) D Whips were common here in the brush and several other species were collected.
in the Gila Mts Chucks were quite common and 5 were collected.
Dips were observed at Dublin.
We hunted in the sand hill-rocky hill 5 mi. E. of Yuma and got a Cally but no Umas were seen.
1 Red Racer L DOR Fort Yuma. Irrigated fields.
(Continued May 18th)

Sunday June 5, 1932

This morning tried out the rattle vibration machine using a pencil attached to the rattle via a needle. While a few good curves were secured, there is too much interference and the adjustment is too difficult so it cannot be determined whether the same speed is obtained as would be natural. A relay scheme will have to be employed.
In the afternoon brought up to date the field record - field trip book.
Talked with Cook about the coming trip to Tanque Verde mts.
Cook worked this evening until after 7 to clean up influx of rattlers Everything now pickled except a chuck and a gopher.
Worked late tonight making the entries in the annual list series and finished same to June 1st.

Sunday June 12, 1932

This morning we started from Lebec at 7:30; a clear warm morning.
Fort Tejon is distinctly Upper Sonoran. There are high rolling hills covered with heavy brush; very large oaks in the canyons. There is a species of small, thin-stemmed yucca on the hillsides, rather thick in some patches. These do not look favorable for X. vigilis but are not of course, impossible. There are some scattered rocks and rock outcrops (not granite).
We stopped and hunted for about 1/2 hr. (until 8:30) on the Grapevine Creek about 1 mi. N. of Fort Tejon. (Nearer the Fort than Camp Tejon) Skellies are very common here, both on rocks and trees. Utas are fairly plentiful on rocks. Whips are to be seen in the brush. Turned over such yuccas as there were, but found nothing; when dried they amount to little, hardly a suitable protection. There is much granite, but it is hard and jagged and without flakes. Amphibians would be expected along the creek.
At the lower end of the San Joaquin it was comfortably warm - not hot.
1 A.e. occidentalis DOR 3 mi. W. of Maricopa Junction = Emidio Sta.. Fields. Saved
(Continued on Jan 10)

Monday June 13, 1932

Spent the day at MVZ from 11:20 to 5:20.
Saw Drs. Grinnell and Linsdale.
Went through the card file and made records of some of the principal species in which I am interested. Also examined a few specimens. The lists made will be filed by species. Some other observations and locality notes follow:

Lampropeltis getula conjuncta
4 specimens from Todos Santos, Agua Caliente, Eureka and Comondu appear superficially like yumensis, especially the last. In the white bands the scales are all surrounded by dark.

Lampropeltis getula yumensis
The two specimens from El Cajon Canyon (9630-1) are not yumensis; rather they are typical boylii. But the two others from 7 mi E. of Cerro Pueto (10761-2) are very good yumensis. There are others in the collection from Calif. and Arizona.

Lampropeltis mtida
Examined Nos. 11845-6 from Agua
(Continued on Jan 14th)

lwilliams

Thursday June 16, 1932

This morning I called on Mr. Harwell the park naturalist and visited the museum. Of preserved rattlers there are 4 and one alive, all from the immediate vicinity of the park. The seem somewhat like the San Joaquin Valley specimens.
Alive there were 1 rattler, 3 or 4 rubber snakes, 3 Coral kings, skinks, Alligator lizards of both kinds and Rana boylii Also a ring neck much darker than our southern form.
One of the Coral kings lacks red and was classified as boylii. At only two points is there a faint indication of light splitting the black. When placed with a regular Coral king they mated at once. Another has comparatively little red but at least it is evident. The third, with which the black one (a male) mated, had about the usual amount of red.
The afternoon was spend riding around and sight seeing. A good many rocks and logs were turned over. About 8 skellies were seen; they are quite wild. Usually they are on rocks; none was caught.
One skink was caught with some
(Continued Jan 17th)

Friday June 17, 1932

Spend the morning in the museum examining rattlers and talking to naturalists and rangers. Made scale counts on 2 rattlers.
Saw another with the following caption:
"Taken while downing a fence lizard. Collected by A F Hall June 18, 1933, at the top of Bridalveil Falls." This is a small snake with 2 rattles (5.3, 5.7) The lizard is swallowed down to the hind legs. It is a good sized Skelly or might be a S.g. gracilis, but probably not the latter as it is too large.
There is also a large one with the following caption: "Pacific Rattlesnake, killed July 19, 1931, at an elevation of 6500 ft in Tenaya Canyon, Y.N.P. By A W Bell. The cony (Ochotona schisticeps muiri) was removed from the stomach of the snake. The snake measured 43" in length"
At 1 P.M. I talked to a small group of naturalists and rangers on snakes and rattlers in particular showing slides. A fire broke up the proceedings at 2.
Started from Curry's for Glacier Point
(Continued on Jan 18)

Saturday June 18, 1932

In the morning at Glacier Point we caught a few Skellies with a noose. They were quite plentiful on the rocks and rather tame.
We started from Glacier Point at 10:05; a cool clear day. The first stop was at Sentinel Dome. Here a S. graciosuswas noosed on a rock pile within one foot of a snow bank.
Stopped at creek, a deep creek 6.7 mi from Glacier Point between Mono Meadow and Bridalveil Creek and collected 4 adult Rana boylii sierrae and a small T.o. elegans. The Ranas were parked on the bank and took refuge in the grass on the bottom.
One small ??T.o. coushi?? DOR at Elevenmile Trees. We hunted here but got nothing.
An Alligator Lizard evidently webbii was lost on the road at China Well.
1 gopher L DOR Brush Bisset's Ranch.
1 gopher L caught on the road at Bisset's Ranch. Brush. This snake was caught by following the track.

Tuesday June 28, 1932

Today went to El Cajon Rotary Club. Out via University and Bostonia; back via Broadway. Warm in the back country. 37 miles. Nothing seen.
Talked today to Dr. Knox about the recent rattler fatality. The patient reached him about 1 3/4 hrs after the accident. He was bitten on the hand while reaching ??torn?? to overturn a board; the snake was under the board. He was bitten on the right hand near the basal knuckles. One fang punctured a vein. Both fang mar marks were visible. A tourniquet had been placed on the upper arm. He was driven in by other parties - not by himself as reported. They stopped at Alpine and were unable to get aid.
Dr. Knox gave 1 tube Mulfords Antivenom intramuscularly and applied suction removing considerable blood. The tourniquet was then loosened. The patient was badly frightened but his heart was good.
There seems to have been considerable of a mix up at County Hospital resulting in delay. Also a mix up re doctors.

Notes:

lwilliams

reaching ??torn?? to overturn a board

Saturday July 2, 1932

This afternoon at 1:30 went out to get Philip at Camp Fletcher Cuyamaca. Went by way of Broadway, Grossmont at the Old Viejas grade. From Cuyamaca we went to Julian, then out through the Narrows to the Kane Spring's Junction and then returned via El Centro and the Highway. Miles in the county in daylight 101; total miles 289. Reached home at 11:10. It was comfortably warm in the back country and mountains and very hot on the desert even at 6 pm. To reach the best collecting roads after dark we took a side run from El Centro to Calexico and returned via Seeley. We drove slowly on the best part of the road and probably missed nothing. Also we certainly missed no snakes "in the round" from Mt. Springs in. The lack of material indicates once more the waste of time involved in hunting at this time of year.
1 Cally alive 4 mi. E of county line. Several others were seen between 5 and 6 pm alive on the highway.
(Continued on July 1)

Monday July 18, 1932

Cook completed his work today. As of this date all rattlers have been checked. Thus all are finished up to No. 9223; also the S.D.N.H. Soc. specs. are also complete.
As of this date all specimens have been pickled except a dozen or so just received.
No foreign specimens are at hand except 9 from MVZ which require checking

Today saw a young ruber (M) from El Cajon, killed by Mrs. Ceveling

Wednesday August 24, 1932

This morning went out to Flinn Springs to look at lines. Quite hot in the back country. 50 miles.
1 R. lecontei DOR M Flinn Spr. Brush-rocks
1 C.c. oreganus DOR M Fletcher Hills Lt brush.
In the afternoon went to La Jolla to meeting of the staff. 22 miles nothing seen.
Today Sumner gave me a rattler (C.c. oreganus) which he had had in captivity for 3 years since Sep. 1929. It is very vicious; rattles violently when approached and strikes at any object brought nearby. He doesn't know how many rattles it had when he first got it; maybe 3 to 5. It now has 10 complete rattles and is 860 mm long.

Sunday September 4, 1932

Spend the entire day and evening on fang correlation with head size and total length; also head size with total length. Fang measurements are very difficult. Developed for the first time the theory that the fangs come into the sockets alternately and not as Weir Mitchell states from the inside outward.

Thursday September 15, 1932

Recd today from Nat Hist Soc a Cnemidophorus tessellatus from La Jolla.
Examined the rattler picked up by Bogert at Shimopovi after the dance. The mouth is in bad shape. All the fangs have been cut out and there are deep holes here. Even the rudimentary fangs are gone. Maxillary sockets are gone. There are cuts on each side - not just torn out.

Saturday October 1, 1932

Pickled 32 little rattlers today. Spent the rest of the time working on head rations until late at night.

On Sept 18th E.V. Potler shot a large female Pacific Rattler at Japatul. Contained 10 young in capsules, evidently just ready for birth. One was loosened by the shot and this he saved; the others were destroyed. This one was kept until Oct 1 when it died; evidently difficulty with shedding. It's dimensions then were L269-T19 ? H 17.8, W 17g. It had not yet shed and therefore had the pre button. This was loosened and found to come off as a part of the skin

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 01/11/2012 03:12 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:28 PM

Sunday October 9, 1932

Began to rain this AM. Stayed indoors all day.
In the evening went out in the heave rain and got 9 Ensatinas. 6 were walking along close to the house foundations. Here the rain was kept off by the eaves. It was moist but not wet. 2 of the others were found along the road where partially protected by an overhanging bank, the other in the same position relative to a bank. this was about 8 PM and the rain was falling heavily. Would have got more but the flashlight was poor and had not suitable boots or rain coat.

Nothing seen on the way to town. It was hot and sultry. 62 miles.

Lampropeltis getula

California King snake

L.g. boylii refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a ringed pattern.

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
